# Unit Function Exam — Setup & Deployment Guide

A Next.js + TypeScript + Supabase + Tailwind training exam app, styled in a
GE Vernova–inspired professional theme (navy / teal / green accent), with a
lightweight 3D turbine hero, full trainee exam flow, and an admin dashboard
for question/category/result management and Excel import.

---

## 1. Project structure

```
exam-app/
├── app/
│   ├── page.tsx                       Home / Start Exam ("/")
│   ├── layout.tsx, globals.css
│   ├── exam/page.tsx                  Active exam ("/exam")
│   ├── result/[attemptId]/page.tsx    Final score screen
│   ├── admin/
│   │   ├── page.tsx                   Dashboard ("/admin")
│   │   ├── login/page.tsx
│   │   ├── questions/page.tsx         Question bank management
│   │   ├── categories/page.tsx        Categories & rules
│   │   ├── results/page.tsx           All results + filters + CSV export
│   │   ├── results/[attemptId]/page.tsx  Detailed answers for one attempt
│   │   └── import/page.tsx            Excel import UI
│   └── api/
│       ├── exam/start, question, answer, submit   (trainee exam engine)
│       └── admin/login, questions, categories, import, results/export
├── components/    Header, Logo, TurbineHero3D, QuestionCard, AnswerOption,
│                  ProgressBar, AdminSidebar, StatCard, ResultsTable,
│                  CategoryStatusTable, ImportReport
├── lib/           supabaseClient.ts, supabaseAdmin.ts, examEngine.ts,
│                  requireAdmin.ts, types.ts
├── scripts/       importExcel.ts   (CLI import tool)
├── supabase/      schema.sql       (tables + indexes + RLS policies)
├── middleware.ts  protects /admin/* routes
├── public/        put logo.svg/png, turbine.glb, fonts/ here
├── data/          put source-questions.xlsx here for CLI import
└── .env.local.example
```

---

## 2. Supabase setup

1. Create a project at supabase.com.
2. Go to **SQL Editor → New query**, paste the entire contents of
   `supabase/schema.sql`, and run it. This creates every table (profiles,
   categories, questions, category_rules, app_settings, exam_attempts,
   exam_attempt_questions, exam_answers), all indexes/relationships, and
   Row Level Security policies.
3. Go to **Project Settings → API** and copy:
   - Project URL → `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL`
   - `anon` public key → `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY`
   - `service_role` key → `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` (keep this secret —
     server-only, never shipped to the browser)

---

## 3. Local setup

```bash
cd exam-app
npm install
cp .env.local.example .env.local
# edit .env.local with your Supabase keys + a strong ADMIN_PASSWORD
npm run dev
```

Open http://localhost:3000.

### Admin access
Go to `/admin/login` and enter the `ADMIN_PASSWORD` you set in `.env.local`.
This is the "simple password protected admin" option from the brief —
fast to set up, no user accounts needed. (If you later want real
per-admin logins, the SQL schema already includes a `profiles.role =
'admin'` path with matching RLS policies — wire up Supabase Auth and
swap the `middleware.ts` check for a session lookup instead of the
cookie check.)

---

## 4. Import your question bank

**Option A — from the browser (recommended):**
Go to `/admin/import`, upload your `.xlsx` file, click **Run Import**.
You'll see a report: how many questions were parsed, how many were valid,
how many were imported, every category found, and a list of any problem
rows (missing options, unmatched correct answers, categories under 2
questions). Fix problems in your source file and re-upload — re-importing
only adds questions, it never deletes existing ones.

**Option B — from the command line:**
```bash
mkdir -p data
cp /path/to/your/file.xlsx data/source-questions.xlsx
npm run import:excel
```
Review the generated `import-report.json` in the project root.

> **Important — review correct answers.** Your original file had mixed
> English/Hebrew formatting across its 25 category tabs, and a handful
> of questions could not be parsed with full confidence (this is reported
> explicitly, not silently guessed). After importing, check
> `/admin/questions`, especially for any category flagged in the report,
> and compare each `correct_answer` against its `explanation` before
> trusting it for scoring.

---

## 5. Logo, font, and 3D model

Drop these into `/public` (filenames are hardcoded, no code changes needed):

| File | Purpose | If missing |
|---|---|---|
| `logo.svg` or `logo.png` | Header logo | Falls back to a clean "UNIT FUNCTION EXAM" text wordmark |
| `turbine.glb` | 3D hero model | Falls back to an animated procedural placeholder turbine (cylinders/boxes), still professional-looking |
| `fonts/your-font.woff2` | Brand font | Uncomment the `@font-face` block in `app/globals.css`; otherwise Inter/system font is used |

No fake GE logo or font was created anywhere in this codebase — both are
opt-in via these file drops only.

---

## 6. Deploying to Vercel

1. Push this project to a GitHub repo.
2. Go to vercel.com → **New Project** → import the repo.
3. In **Environment Variables**, add the same 4 values from `.env.local`:
   `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL`, `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY`,
   `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY`, `ADMIN_PASSWORD`.
4. Deploy. Vercel auto-detects Next.js — no build config changes needed.
5. After deploy, re-upload `logo.svg`/`turbine.glb` isn't needed if they're
   already committed inside `/public` in your repo — Vercel deploys
   `/public` as-is.

---

## 7. Adjusting the passing score / explanation visibility

Both live in the `app_settings` table (single row, id = 1):
```sql
update app_settings set passing_score = 0.80, show_explanations_to_trainee = false;
```
There's no dedicated admin UI screen for this yet (the brief's other 20+
features were prioritized) — adjust directly in Supabase's **Table
Editor → app_settings**, or add a small settings form to
`/admin` calling a new `/api/admin/settings` route following the same
pattern as the other admin API routes.

---

## 8. Testing checklist

- [ ] Run the SQL schema, confirm all 8 tables exist in Supabase Table Editor
- [ ] Import your Excel file via `/admin/import`, confirm 25 categories appear
- [ ] Check `/admin` dashboard — confirm every category shows "OK" (≥2 questions); fix any flagged as "NOT ENOUGH"
- [ ] On `/`, enter a trainee name, click **Start Exam**
- [ ] Confirm the exam has exactly 50 questions (`Question 1 of 50` ... `50 of 50`)
- [ ] Answer a few, click **Back**, confirm your previous selections are still highlighted
- [ ] Try **Submit** before answering everything — confirm it's blocked with a clear message
- [ ] Answer all 50, submit, confirm the score screen shows correct %, correct/wrong counts, Pass/Fail
- [ ] Check Supabase: a new row in `exam_attempts`, 50 rows in `exam_attempt_questions`, 50 rows in `exam_answers`
- [ ] On `/admin/results`, confirm the new attempt appears; open it and confirm all 50 detailed answers are correct
- [ ] Test filters (name / pass-fail / date range) and **Export CSV**
- [ ] Test `/admin/questions` add/edit/delete, and `/admin/categories` add/edit-count/delete
- [ ] Resize the browser to a phone width — confirm Home, Exam, and Admin pages remain usable
- [ ] Confirm `/admin/*` redirects to `/admin/login` when not authenticated

---

## 9. Known limitations / what to harden before heavy production use

- Admin auth is a single shared password (no per-admin accounts/audit
  trail). Fine for a small training team; upgrade to Supabase Auth +
  `profiles.role='admin'` for multi-admin accountability.
- The 3D turbine placeholder is intentionally simple low-poly geometry,
  not a realistic model — supply a real `.glb` for production polish.
- Excel parsing is heuristic-based because the source file's 25 tabs use
  inconsistent layouts; always review the import report before trusting
  a freshly imported question bank in a real exam.
